A UWC educational expert says institutions of higher learning should do more to ease learners into the tertiary curriculum. CAPE TOWN - A University of the Western Cape (UWC) educational expert says institutions of higher learning should do more to ease learners into the tertiary curriculum.The institution's Deputy Dean of Teaching and Learning says more should also be done by government to ensure social improvement in the three worst performing provinces in the 2016 matric results.Basic Education Minister Angie Motshekga on Wednesday announced the Eastern Cape, Limpopo and KwaZulu-Natal were the three worst performing provinces in last year's final matric exams.UWC's Professor Rajendran Govender adds that tertiary institutions should make a concerted effort to ease learners into the university curriculum. In the first year they must nurture the candidates and prepare them via appropriate programmes and strengthen their critical thinking and comprehension. Govender adds that a challenge still remains for more learners to take up pure mathematics combined with having the teachers equipped to teach the subject.To get your 2016 matric results go to EWN s special matric results page. Share the page with your friends.(Edited by Zamangwane Shange)